re 1148":"before 1148","1132":"1132","1252":"1252","1185":"1185","1085":"1085","1180":"1180","1216":"1216","1248":"1248","1115":"1115","1148":"1148","1155":"1155","1089":"1089","from 1145 to 1181":"from 1145 to 1181","Northumbria, England":"Northumbria, England","Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Hoggal","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish and Scottish: variant of   Hagan   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Hagan","meanings":["Irish (Tyrone, Armagh, and Derry): shortened Anglicized form of   O'Hagan  , from Gaelic <b>Ó hÁgáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Ógán</i>’, a personal name from a diminutive of <i>óg</i> ‘young’. Compare   Hogan  .","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Hagan</i>, or <i>Hagen</i>, mostly representing Old Danish <i>Haghni</i> or Old Norse <i>Hǫgni</i> ‘protector, patron’, especially in Norfolk, where the name is well attested in the 12th- and early 13th-centuries. It may have been reinforced by Norman use of ancient Germanic <i>Hagano</i>, <i>Hageno</i>, <i>Hagino</i>, but there is no certain evidence for this in Anglo-Norman England. In Norfolk the name was confused with the Middle English personal name <i>Hakun</i>. It also developed to   Hane   and   Hayne   (see   Hain  ).","English: variant of <b>Hacon</b> with voicing of the intervocalic consonant, from the Middle English personal name <i>Hacun</i> (Old Norse <i>Hákun</i>, from ancient northern Germanic elements meaning ‘horse’ + ‘kindred’). <b>Hacon</b> is found mainly in Norfolk and Suffolk."]}]},{"name":"Gilbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. This was the name of the founder of the only native British religious order (abolished at the Dissolution of the Monasteries),  St Gilbert  of Sempringham (  ?1083–1189 ), in whose honour it is still sometimes bestowed, especially among Roman Catholics. It gained a wider currency in the 19th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gilbert de Hoggal was born in 1115, in Northumberland, England, his father, Humphrey de Hoggell, was 31 and his mother, Isabella, was 26. He had at least 3 sons. He died in 1180, in his hometown, at the age of 65."},"et":{"1115–1180":"1115–1180","1132–Male":"1132–Surnud","1180–1252":"1180–1252","1185–1216":"1185–1216","–1248":"–1248","1085–1155":"1085–1155","1089–1148":"1089–1148","before 1148":"enne 1148","1132":"1132","1252":"1252","1185":"1185","1085":"1085","1180":"1180","1216":"1216","1248":"1248","1115":"1115","1148":"1148","1155":"1155","1089":"1089","from 1145 to 1181":"1145 kuni 1181","Northumbria, England":"Northumbria, England","Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, England"},"fi":{"1115–1180":"1115–1180","1132–Male":"1132–Kuollut","1180–1252":"1180–1252","1185–1216":"1185–1216","–1248":"–1248","1085–1155":"1085–1155","1089–1148":"1089–1148","before 1148":"ennen vuotta 1148","1132":"1132","1252":"1252","1185":"1185","1085":"1085","1180":"1180","1216":"1216","1248":"1248","1115":"1115","1148":"1148"